default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn establishing the team and its working practices we have had to rely heav
defaultily upon those that have already developed practices and methods which are proven. In particular we have drawn upon the published outputs from BIS and the DEFRA/NE/EA family. Within the wider Government framework we have found that there is little to draw 
defaultupon from the ‘cultural’ sector, with the exception of audience research or insight.
default&#xa0;
default8
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne aspect of the teams work is to begin to move towards a more pro-active model of working. Currently English Heritage along with the majority of those in the sector, wh
defaultether in local government or the commercial sectors, operates within a highly reactive working environment. The need to prioritise and manage reducing resources, whist maintaining, or improving the protection for the historic environment, are very current 
defaultreasons for adopting this approach.
default&#xa0;
default9
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow do Government departments make use of horizon scanningdefault - For reasons explained above English Heritage has very limited experience of interacting with Government departments or NDPBs. We therefore do not feel in the position to make any general statements about how the products of horizon scanning are being us
defaulted. That said those few times where we have engaged with other NDPBs in their horizon scanning exercises our contributions and views have been welcomed.
default&#xa0;
default10
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow effective is horizon scanning in Government? Do Ministers and senior officials consider horizon scdefaultanning outputs appropriately?default – For the same reasons as above we are not in a position to give answers to these questions. We have observed that 
defaultthere are often what may be termed behavioural reasons why horizon scanning is treated with degrees of sceptici
defaultsm, which from our position are unwarranted. 
default&#xa0;
default11
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat changes could be made to improve existing horizon scanning activity?default default– From our limited experience we’ve noted the confusion that surrounds the different usages of the term horizon scanning, along with ot
defaulther allied terms such as foresight. In paragraph 5 of his report Jon Day highlights this issue and goes onto to define horizon scanning for the purposes of the report. We would like to see this broadened out such that there were common terms and definition
defaults used across Government and the NDPBs.
default 
default&#xa0;
default12
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWill the recommendations made in Jon Day’s review of cross-government horizon scanning capability address current shortcomings?default default– Again from our limited experience it is likely that these recommendations will impro
defaultve the situation. The Day report recognises the need for both top down and bottom up approaches and we feel that the recommendations better cover the former and there is still work to be done to address the latter.
default&#xa0;default13
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat progress has been made implementingdefault these?default defaultNot aware of any apart from the call for evidence.
default&#xa0;default14
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow effective is the Government at responding to policy or regulatory challenges presented by new technologies?default default– One issue with new technologies is the apparent late engagement by Government and 
defaultits NDPBs which means that these technologies are often developed without any reference to wider implications. Additionally this late engagement means that any necessary policy or regulatory matters are not considered alongside the development of the techn
defaultology and therefore anything needed is often seen as an afterthought. Better horizon scanning should be able to pick up these developments and help avoid this scenario.
default&#xa0;default15
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have one observation to make on the 3D printing case study. The ability of laser sc
defaultanners to capture artefacts and objects and then to send the data to a remote 3D printer opens up many opportunities across the historic environment sector. One such opportunity is the potential for museums to make available 3D images of artefacts which co
defaultuld then be printed out remotely, in effect a development of the collections on line approach which currently uses still or moving images. The ability for people to actually handle the object brings an added dimension which cannot be under estimated.
